segments.text: If somebody handed you a check for a million dollars and it had one restriction on it, you must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you can decide what you want A&M to do with it.
If you could give A&M a million dollars, what would you tell them to do with your gift?
Well, I'm afraid it wouldn't go to education.
It would go to the activities programs of the Corps because I still believe that the Corps is a good education.
What activities would you have?
What money I do give mostly goes to the capital.
Okay.

And I'm sure you can understand why, because, but I do belong to a number of other things, you know, but I jointly have a scholarship, a presidential scholarship and a core scholarship and that sort of stuff, but those things are going to come along anyway.
But the million dollars to me was going to make sure
that they have these things to keep attracting them into the Corps.
And if it's scholarships, it does it great, and I'm sure it is.
To what former faculty, students, staff, whatever, to what people connected with A&M do you feel the most grateful for what they meant to you and why?
Well, I think I've already told you what Dr. Harrington meant to me.
I had one of my military instructors, it was then Captain Roy Smith.
He was an Aggie, but I didn't know anything else about him.
I was very patient and helpful.
So you kind of looked up to those guys.
I mentioned Majalis, that was my XO, my battery.
You kind of, you know, sometimes you want to talk to an older guy about what should I do about this out of the other.
And if you'll turn this machine off there.
What have we not covered about your student years that we should have?
Oh, I don't think there's a whole lot.
I wrote down some things.
Let me look real quick.
The class of 49, you know, had three different starting classes, and then they, what we call, souped us up, gave us privileges ahead of time.
So we ended up wearing our boots senior year when actually one academic semester we were juniors.
So we had a semester of college left, and new seniors were coming in and taking command.
So we still were under military contract and so forth, and they moved us into dorm one.
And there were two floors of us and two companies.
We still wore the uniform.
We still had to march to Chow and do everything else the Corps had, except we didn't have to send more information.
And we were kind of a maverick group.
Nobody loved us anymore.
So that was just another year of living in the dormitory, wearing the uniform, and not really belonging because we were all seniors.
And you didn't have to worry with any of the,
We had no, we just had a place to sleep and whatever.
We didn't have to do the other stuff.
In fact, they didn't want us to mess with them.
There was a new group taking command.
But I don't think there's probably been another one.
Maybe there was somewhere in history.
Okay, anything else?
I was going to ask you a thing about this.
Okay, the last question of this part.
What feelings do you carry in your heart about Texas A&M now?
How do you feel about A&M?
Well, to me, next to my immediate family, it's the closest to my heart.
Everywhere I go, I think, you know, I'm an Aggie, and I don't hesitate to let people know that.
I think I have more stickers on my Lincoln than these guys have on their pickup trucks.
I'm very sensitive to spotting ivies.
And I'll tell you one little story.
Just very recently, we go to Barksdale to the commissary, and I had on a t-shirt like this probably, because I wear them 98 times a time.
And there was a handsome-looking black guy coming down there, a big old boy.
I wouldn't fathom him.
He had on a Texas ivy shirt.
And so I went over to him and I said, I'm Tom Parsons, class of 49.
He looked at me and, you're what?
And shook hands with me.
You're an Aggie, aren't you?
I'm an Aggie.
Oh, you mean this?
And he said, I work for Goodwill and we're stocking groceries.
good will to give me a shirt.
So anyway, I don't hesitate to spot the Aggies and they do very close to me and just these gentlemen, I feel real good when I meet one of them and sometimes they even recognize my name.
Not too long ago,

Oh, three or four years ago, Grace and I were out at the cow barn one day and just wandering around, nobody there, and this kid walked up and I introduced myself and, are you related to Colonel Parsons?
This is named after him?
I said, yeah, that's me.
And he said, oh, I thought he was dead.
So I know they know me well out there.
But I don't think my feelings are any different than 99% of the others.
I just don't know.
I've never heard anybody put A&M down that survived A&M.
Maybe some put them down that didn't make it, but that was their own fault.
Let's quit with that.
Testing 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.
Testing, testing, testing, testing.
This is the second interview with Colonel Parsons.
This is the 20th of September.
We're in room 207.
in the Evans Library and today we will be concentrating on his years here as Commandant and then as the Campus Security and Parking and Traffic.
I didn't get that title exactly correct.
Security and Traffic.
Security and Traffic.
To introduce this part of it, you were on active duty in the Army.
How did you and A&M have any link about possibly coming here as commandant?
Well, I was stationed at Fort Carson, Colorado, and at that time I was commanding the 4th Infantry Division Artillery, which had six battalions in it.
I'd just about come to the end of my command tour time.
I was within six months of going to be transferred anyway.
And I heard about the job being opened and then I heard that Bon, Billy Bon, had been selected.
Well, Billy screwed up and made general.
He's a classmate of mine.
Well, I heard through Billy that, hey, there's an opening down there.
took leave and hopped on an airplane and flew down.
I didn't tell anybody where I was going but my wife, because obviously my general and I didn't get along anyway.
I was smarter than him and he didn't believe it.
Anyway, I came down and
I can't even think of his name now.
General, Dean of Men.
Hannigan?
Dean Hannigan was in the chair.
Of course, he understood military people pretty well.
He took me around and talked to me for a long time.
Anyway, Dr. Williams wasn't there at the time.
And he said, no, you're going to have to come and visit Dr. Williams if we around here agree that you're the man.
So I hopped on the plane and went back to Colorado.
And I got another call from him.
I flew back down.
And Dr. Williams evidently was on some other mission at the time.
So back I go.
And meanwhile, it was summer camp time.
And the cadets were at Fort Riley, Kansas.

and Dr. Williams went to visit the cadets and I went over for an interview with him there and met the cadets that were the Army ones that were out there at the camp and everything went well and Dr. Williams said if you can get out of your command, you're the man for the job.
That was not difficult.
My general was more than happy to see me leave.
We didn't see eye to eye on a few things.
I headed out for A&M in the summer of 1971.
When you talked to Dr. Williams, do you remember, what did he, did he ask you questions?
He asked me personal questions.
What seemed to be his concerns?
Yes.
Well, he was very interested in females.
He was interested in Navy ROTC.
He was interested in not so much my educational background.
He didn't ask me much about my military background because Dean Hannigan had already found out.
I mean, it's easy to find out that stuff.
But mostly it was just kind of social.
And then we went to the, they always have a party for the Aggies at these things, and we went to that.
And, of course, I made it good with the cadets that were there because, you know, I fitted in pretty well with them, I guess.
Describe your first impressions of Dr. Williams.
Oh, I was a little frightened in a way.
I mean, you know, he's the easy man to talk to, but after all, you know, he's the president and I'm the colonel or whatever.
There's a big gap in that.
And he was very polite to me.
We had a couple of drinks and, you know, I guess he talked to me maybe 30 minutes.
Did he at all mention his World War II military record?
I didn't know at that time .
And so you came then in?
Summer of 71.
Summer of 71.
And he had come in November 1, 1970.
Right.
Colonel McCoy was the commandant then and he had already retired and they let him stay on active duty until I came in.
So you then are signed as a U.S. Army Professor of Military Science.
Yeah, but you were officially still a member of the Army.
You weren't?
Oh yeah.
That's what I thought.
Okay.
Describe the core staff of the military and military science when you got here.
Well, we were Army and Air Force, and of course I had the responsibility for the Army's ROTC program, and I had
a lieutenant colonel who was my deputy, who in a sense ran the Air Force, the Army ROTC.
The Air Force had a colonel, Crosland was his name, Bob Crosland.
And from the ROTC point of view, we were separate, just like the difference between political science and engineering, I guess.
But I had 18 officers and seven enlisted men.
And the enlisted men, some of them were instructors because they were better qualified in a lot of areas.
And we had four civilian employees, Department of the Army civilian employees.
and one university employee there.
So it was a fairly large operation.
The Air Force was about the same in size and whatever.
The Army had a few more cadets than the Air Force did.
For the Commandant's Office, it was totally, in my opinion, understaffed.
I had to pull Don Johnson out of the Army program and make him the deputy, and that's one of my Army people, and I'm already out of the flight.
The Air Force provided me a major, and the rest of the people, which was one, two, five people in the office,
and three male civilians who were so-called advisors to the Corps, one of whom was Malin.
And they, of course, tried to keep track of, you know, problems in the dorms and this, that, and the other, and yell practices and so forth.
And that was the size of the staff.
About, of all of the staff, about how many of them were Aggies in their undergraduate training?
Well, I'd say the Army ROTC officers were probably 75% and the Air Force more or less about the same percentage.
Of course, Aggies were fighting to get the job.
You didn't have to beg them to come to A&M.
The problem was getting them to release them to come to A&M.
Because an ROTC assignment is not the most productive for your career.
Yeah, yeah.
And I had had a previous ROTC assignment at Boston College.
And so my career was, well, my career was okay.
It didn't hurt my career, but it put you off track for a while.
And the corps offices then were.
They were all active duty.
No, no, I'm sorry.
The location of the offices for the commandant were all in the trigon?
All in the trigon.
Well, let me rephrase that.
These three civilians, we had a little office in these little, what do they call them, lounges, and so they had an office there.
The, and what was the, what was the Corps enrollment that fall?
Do you remember?
I can tell you pretty close, about 2,300.
About 2,300.
We never fell below 2,000 when I was there.
and describe as you come in that fall, describe the activities of the Corps compared with what you remembered them when you were a student here.
What had changed and what hadn't changed?
One thing is, we mentioned it earlier, they wore their boots.
You know, we never did ours.
You know, they wore them almost everywhere.
And the other is that the, there was a pretty much, not as much segregation as there was in the Air Force here and the Army over on the other side and so forth.
There was pretty much.
You didn't have to be an Army ROTC cadet to be in an Air Force outfit.
In other words, they were mixed up based on the academic area more than anything else because they were assigned, basically, if they didn't have a choice of outfits,
If they were an engineer, we had companies that were oriented that way, and liberal arts were oriented and so forth, which I thought was a very good idea.
We had a medical company, which was a very good one, engineers and so forth, signal.
So those things were a little bit different, but I didn't really...
Some of the things we used to do, like have a drum and bugle in the morning, I always loved that.
That never happened when I came back.
Used to have the Reveille gun fire and that went away when the veterans came back and cemented the cannon.
So those little things were there, but the mansions were the same, the mess hall, same sort of deal.
They did things that we never did, like lighting the napkins and burning them on people and that sort of stuff.
The food was the same names and all that stuff, and a lot better.
And the dormitories, they had not changed.
Pretty much just like they were, except that they were allowed upperclassmen
build their own rooms, you know, juniors and seniors.
And some of them were pretty lavish and didn't matter back in my days.
They all looked pretty much alike.
And there were no room inspections by the Bulls anymore.
We did this.
We had officers responsible for certain outfits and they'd go through, but as far as inspections, we didn't do those.
Did you, were there any problems that you inherited
to which you had to give your immediate attention.
No, it was really very easy to move into the job.
I think had I not been an Aggie, it would have been impossible.
I respect that choice that the commandant should always be an Aggie, and I still think he should always be an Aggie.
I agree with you, but explain why you feel that way.
Because they are totally accepted by the Corps when they come in.
They don't have to go there and say,
And these are core agas I'm talking about.
They don't have to go over and sell themselves.
And the core, if they don't like you, you might as well pack your bags.
And I think it's pretty much that way now.
They won't come in to see you if they don't know that you understand what they're trying to do and how they do it.
And let's see, the corps officers for 71, 72 had already been selected before you got here, hadn't they?
Yeah.
So that you didn't have any hands.
I had nothing to do, but I sure Tom Stanley was a, you may know Tom, I think he's a lawyer here in town now.
Tom Stanley.
Oh, Stanley.
He was just outstanding.
He was gung-ho military.
He went airborne, ranger, served in the Army, and then become a lawyer.
I haven't seen him since.
Did anybody, Dr. Williams or Dean Hannigan or anybody give you any directions of things to do or not to do?
Well, not really, other than Dean Hannigan, you know, wanted to tone the hazing as much as I could.
We didn't, the women part had not come up and didn't for a couple of years.
But nobody really came in and said, well, I want this done, that done, the other done.
And Dr. Williams didn't either.
Now, if there was a problem with some mama or something, I heard from Dr. Williams,
And sometimes, you know, he had a temper.
And sometimes he was, because they hassled him and I wouldn't blame him.
He'd pass it down to me and he'd jump me and whatever.
I'd get to the bottom of it, get him straightened out and go up and talk to him and he'd,
You know, you're smiling exactly now.
Give some examples of those problems that you remember.
Well, in the band, I see there was one mother called him, and then this was in the nighttime, and her son hadn't been able to wear his underwear in 30 days, and she wanted it stopped.
Well, the time it got to me, I didn't know that.
I mean, I don't do underwear inspections, and
Nobody told me anything else, and Dr. Williams, of course, let me know, and I'd go over there and find out that they'd taken their footlocker.
Well, they didn't do that in my days either, I might mention, and so it was retaliation.
They couldn't wear their underwear until they got his footlocker back.
So I got his footlocker back and I got the underwear privileges.
It's that sort of stuff.
They were not big problems.
I had a woman problem with one of the L leaders.
His cousin was staying in the dormitory for the weekend and the other members weren't too fond of one of the latrines being closed off to them.
show the curve and have a place and that sort and I was able to, you know, that was pretty easy to solve.
I didn't take them off of the elevator, but I took them off of this command position.
And did anybody give you any directions about the hazing that they thought was going on when you?
Not in general.
It was usually on specific incidents that happened.
It was
I don't think it was, it was nowhere near as bad as it was when I was there.
And so far as I know, the board was not in the dormitory.
I think it probably happened at beer brush they had off campus and things like that.
But it wasn't, and we didn't have these deals where they throw water out of the dormitory windows and drown them out.
We didn't do that and I didn't like that too much.
But I couldn't have stopped it.
It was one of those things that wasn't big enough issues to go over there and hassle about.
So I pretty much could go in stride.
Now the corps commander usually was very, very cooperative, and of all of them I had,
And if there was a big problem, you got them and they really hit us right down.
If they agree with you, if they don't, they'll tell you.
And they say, this is a better way to do it.
And they're right.
I mean, these kids, you know, they're pretty mature.
In the six years, which, to which corps commanders would you give the, I'm not going to ask you the negative, who were the best corps commanders you worked with?
Well, Scott Everhard.
You may know Scott.
He's a very, very dear friend now.
Tom Stanley was very good.
I had one that I had to get rid of.
Joe Chandler was a good one, but he was not among the top.
Mike Gentry was outstanding, but I selected him, but I was gone when he served, but I know he was great.
because we knew from the day he came he's going to be our corps commander.
When you became the new commandant, what were your goals?
What did you hope to achieve?

Well, my primary goal was providing officers for the service, and with emphasis on Army, although I tried to be as green-coated as I could, but that was, you know, that was, we were in the war too then,
early stages of the Vietnam War, fairly early stages of it.
And so I worked real hard in programs for them as the Air Force was working for their programs.
And we had no real conflict.
When we had recruiting sessions and so forth, we didn't go around saying, hey, you don't want to get in the Air Force.
You don't want to do this, that, and the other.
That's all I know.
I know I didn't.
Now, when people came into my office, you know, when they come in with a freshman, I talked to everybody I could.
And although I'm not an Army aviator, I was a crew member of airborne command post.
They used to fly around for the nuclear war.
And I had wings, so I must admit I wore my wings because, and strictly, I usually didn't wear them.
There are a lot of these kids that say, well, I want to fly.
And I'd say, yeah, well, the Air Force got a good program.
I said, the Army does, too.
And, you know, the Army has more pilots than the Air Force does, and still does, because of the helicopters.
But that's about the only thing I did.
And I insisted on doing the new student orientations because, first of all, I do a pretty good job in public speaking, getting the crowd with me, and I work very hard and so forth.
I didn't try to sell the Army or anything.
I just talked about all the programs.
I didn't talk ROTC too much.
I only talked core activities.
I don't know.
You might have seen one of my sessions or whatever.
I used to do them with
I can't even think of a name.
I love him to death.
He always tells us the story about the three-legged dog.
Doctor, he retired years ago.
He'll come to me in a minute.
But in his new student conferences they used to have.
Anyway, there was no, the military corps thing was not a conflict.
It was a marriage more than a conflict.
Did you, what was your goal in terms of Corps membership size?
We always wanted to fill the quad.
And that would have been about twenty?
About twenty-two, twenty-three hundred, something like that.
And one year, we did have to open up a couple of the dormitories.
I've forgotten which one it was, but we had a real good recruiting there.
I've got the numbers in here.
I'll dig it out.
And I think the numbers were based not on any, I mean, these are kids who wanted to come to A&M, but based on the war business, too.
And we did have some programs that we introduced
were very popular like we were the first ROTC unit to be allowed to go to jump school.
The Air Force, I mean the Academies were going and my Sergeant Major happened to work for General Westmoreland and he was going home jumping out of airplanes anyway and he says, why don't we do this?
Sergeant Major McDonnell, who used to be the Chief of Police.
And I said, well, I don't know.
I'll talk to the Army.
And he said, no, I'm going to do better than that.
And he could grab the phone and call it up and says, I want to talk to General Westmoreland.
And he did.
And General Westmoreland said, I don't know any reason why these people who are under contract can't do this.
Anyway, so we started it.
And we were the first to go.
And the next year, they had Sergeant Major
said to me that we're going to sign up a hundred cadets to go this year to jump school.
I said, great.
He said, I told them all if I got a hundred signed up that you would go.
And I said, that ain't so great.
I said, I'm not going to go to jump school.
I said, I have no interest in that.
He said, well, you don't have to do it like everybody else.
There's a senior officer program.
You've got to just have a good physical and whatever.
I said, no way, but you tell me you promised those kids.
I said, all right, this is what I'm going to do.
I'm going to call my boss and ask, I'll have to have permission.
And my boss, thank goodness, said, no way are you going to go to jump school.
So I didn't go.
And they understood that part of it.
It wasn't my cowardice, although I wanted a part of it.
But we also had cadets, we were the first ROTC cadets to go to ranger school.
We saw a lot of them through ranger school.
And they always come out number one, as they did in jump school and summer camps.
One year we had cadets that were number one in all Army, Air Force, and other schools that they went to.
As you got here and looked at the quality of the students that were in the Corps,
How did that compare with what you remembered 30 years earlier?
Or 25 years earlier?
Well, they didn't seem to be a whole lot different.
They probably were better educated than we were because the educational system progressed a great deal.
At the time that I was a cadet, you know, we didn't have all these things.
Even now, the 70s are out of date.
But they were pretty bright people.
And really, whoever, I don't know if the TT chose the leadership or not, but whoever did, did a pretty good job.
We used to always have interviews and ended up pretty much doing what the outgoing leadership wanted.
But I don't remember scoring against them except once or twice.
And it originally had a great deal to do with whether you had a contract or not.
You were supposed to have one.
Some of them got the command and then dropped their contract for one reason or another.
And I think I might have mentioned, I personally was opposed to that being a requirement because of my own situation.
And I thought it was very unfair.
And so I deleted that requirement, and I'm proud of that part of my contribution.
Because, I mean, it's great.
That was my job to get officers, but I don't want to get them on the basis of you're not going to be able to be a cadet commander if you don't take a ROTC contract.
Now, in the routine that you developed,
What was the process for selecting the Corps' leadership?
Well, we had the military people make recommendations.
They might have two or three outfits they were responsible for overlooking.
And Malin and his crew made recommendations.
And then we got recommendations from the Corps staff.
And based on those, we pretty generally went along with what the Corps staff recommended.
But did you participate in some of the interviews?
I mean, all when I was president, myself and the Air Force.
